# Technical Direction

## Current Goal

Build a small vertical slice first, not the full game.

The first playable target is:
- One player
- One small test location
- Third-person movement
- Simple interaction
- Daylight timer
- Return-to-base pressure
- One basic enemy/threat later
- No multiplayer until the offline loop feels good

Do not implement future systems early unless the current task explicitly asks for them.

## Engine

- Unity 6000.3.19f1.
- Use C#.
- Use GameObjects and MonoBehaviours.
- Do not use DOTS/ECS.
- Do not use custom engine-level frameworks.

## Rendering

- Use URP.
- Target stylized low-poly visuals.
- Prioritize readability, lighting, fog, silhouettes and atmosphere over realism.
- Do not add visual effects packages unless explicitly approved.

## Input

- Use Unity's New Input System.
- Do not use legacy `Input.GetKey` / `Input.GetAxis` for gameplay.
- Input should be routed through a small input layer, not scattered across gameplay scripts.
- Gameplay scripts should consume intent/actions, not raw key checks.

## Player Controller

- Start with a simple third-person controller.
- Prefer CharacterController for the first prototype.
- Avoid Rigidbody-based player movement unless explicitly approved.
- Movement should be readable and easy to tune.
- Do not implement advanced movement like vaulting, climbing, sliding or parkour unless explicitly requested.

## Camera

- Use Cinemachine if installed/approved.
- Third-person follow camera.
- Keep camera logic separate from player movement.
- Do not build complex camera systems early.

## Interaction System

- Use a simple interface-based interaction system.
- Prefer an `IInteractable` style approach.
- Player detects nearby interactables.
- UI prompt can be added later.
- Interactions should support time costs eventually, but do not build a complex time system until requested.

## Time System

- Time is a core game resource.
- Build time as a central service/system when requested.
- Other systems should ask the time system to spend/advance time rather than each system managing its own clocks.
- Day/night state should eventually be centralized.
- Do not hardcode day/night logic inside unrelated scripts.

## Event System

- Prefer plain C# events or UnityEvents for small local cases.
- For global game events, create a simple explicit event/message layer only when needed.
- Do not add a large event bus framework early.
- Do not create generic abstract event architecture before there are real use cases.

## World Events

- The world should use persistent state, not regenerated layouts.
- Locations remain fixed.
- Events change location state.
- Examples: fire, flood, bandit occupation, looted state, blocked road, infected presence.
- Do not implement procedural world generation unless explicitly requested.
- Procedural encounters/events are preferred over procedural maps.

## Encounter System

- Encounters should be data-driven eventually.
- Start simple.
- A location can have a current encounter/state.
- Encounters should create decisions, not just spawn loot.
- Do not build a full encounter director until a few handcrafted encounters exist.

## Persistence

- The world should eventually remember changes.
- Start with in-memory state for prototypes.
- Add save/load only when there is something worth saving.
- When save/load is added, prefer simple JSON or Unity-serializable data first.
- Do not add databases.

## Inventory

- Do not build a full inventory until requested.
- Start with simple resource counters or picked-up items.
- Avoid complex grids, item rarity, item affixes, durability and RPG loot systems.
- Items should feel grounded and functional.
- No common/rare/epic/legendary loot.

## Combat

- Combat should be simple to execute but expensive to choose.
- Initial combat should be basic and readable.
- Avoid complex ballistics, armor, limb damage or deep medical systems.
- Basic health, damage, bleeding/bandage-type healing is enough when requested.
- Ammo/noise/time cost matter more than mechanical complexity.

## AI / Enemies

- Start with one simple enemy type when requested.
- Prefer simple state machines.
- Avoid behavior trees unless complexity demands it.
- Enemy AI should prioritize clarity over realism.
- Night enemies should feel more dangerous because rules change, not because stats are inflated.

## Noise System

- Noise is an important future mechanic.
- Gunshots, generators, vehicles and tools may create noise.
- Do not build it until requested.
- When added, keep it simple: source, radius, intensity, duration.

## Base System

- Base is an apartment/building that expands functionally.
- Rooms/apartments can become workshops, kitchens, medical rooms, storage, generator rooms, UV defense rooms, etc.
- Base upgrades should be functional first.
- Do not build decoration/custom placement systems early.
- Avoid Fallout-style settlement building until core gameplay works.

## Crafting

- Crafting should be simple and functional.
- No giant recipe trees early.
- Crafting stations can unlock specific actions.
- Start with direct recipes only when requested.

## UI

- Keep UI minimal.
- Use UI Toolkit or uGUI consistently once chosen.
- Do not mix UI frameworks without approval.
- Early prototype UI can be ugly.
- Prioritize debug clarity over polish.

## Multiplayer

- Do not implement multiplayer until the offline loop is fun.
- Do not add Netcode, Photon or Steam networking unless explicitly approved.
- Architect gameplay code so multiplayer can be added later:
  - avoid hard dependencies on local-only assumptions where easy
  - keep gameplay logic separated from input where reasonable
  - avoid static global state for player-specific data

## Audio

- Audio is important for atmosphere.
- Add audio hooks only when requested.
- Prioritize simple one-shot sounds and ambience first.
- Night should eventually be communicated strongly through sound.

## Scenes

- Keep scene count low.
- Current scene: `Main`.
- Do not create extra scenes unless explicitly requested.
- Use test objects/prefabs in the main scene during early prototyping.

## Folder Structure

Use this structure unless explicitly changed:

Assets/
  Art/
  Audio/
  Materials/
  Models/
  Prefabs/
  Scenes/
  Scripts/
    Core/
    Gameplay/
    Input/
    Interaction/
    Time/
    World/
    UI/
    Utilities/
  ScriptableObjects/
  Settings/
  Tests/

Do not create new top-level folders without approval.

## Code Style

- One class per file.
- Names should be clear and boring.
- Prefer explicit dependencies.
- Avoid clever abstractions.
- Keep MonoBehaviours small when reasonable.
- Prefer serialized private fields:
  `[SerializeField] private float moveSpeed;`
- Avoid public mutable fields.
- Avoid magic numbers in logic.
- Add comments only when they explain why, not what.

## Testing / Validation

After changes, always explain:
- how to test in Unity
- expected behavior
- files changed

If possible, keep changes compile-safe.

## Cost / Token Discipline

- Be concise.
- Do not restate the whole architecture.
- Do not summarize unrelated files.
- Do not inspect the whole project unless necessary.
- Prefer editing the smallest number of files.
- Ask before broad refactors.
- Ask before adding packages.
- Ask before generating large systems.